Merge into — upserts, deletes, and slowly changing dimension patterns.

Merge into is the single most-used delta data-manipulation statement in production. It joins a source — your incoming changes — to a target — the table — on a key, and then lets you express what to do in each case. When a row matches you can update it, when it doesn't match you can insert it, and optionally, when a target row is not matched by the source, you can delete it.

There are two patterns the bank uses constantly. The first is slowly changing dimension type one, the overwrite pattern. The customer's city changes, so you just update it in place — no history is kept.

The second is type two, the history pattern. When the customer's city changes, you close the old row by setting a valid-to date and marking it not current, then insert a new row marked current with a fresh valid-from date. This is implemented as two passes — one merge to close the existing rows, and a separate insert of the new active row. The modeling notebook walks through the full pattern inside a pipeline.

One more connection worth making. Merge is also how change-data-capture feeds land into bronze and silver. The apply changes into statement in declarative pipelines is essentially a declarative wrapper around this same merge machinery.
